Getting Started with Deepnote

What and why of Deepnote

Deepnote is a service which provides a web interface to hosted Jupyter notebooks that allows for real time collaboration using notebooks (similar to Google Docs) by multiple people concurrently. This provides a level of interaction that is much more fluid than relying on screen sharing and maintaining versions of workfiles across multiple computers. As it is entirely web based you will be able to access it from any computer with a web browser.

Deepnote is not affiliated with the university in any way, and usage for this course is entirely optional. We believe it will be helpful for collaboration but you are welcomed to use an alternative notebook instance (e.g.EDINA) if you do not want to use Deepnote

Deepnote is built and run by a startup based in Prague and San Francisco, and the product is still relatively new and is rapidly developing. In our use to date it has been reliable and stable but keep in mind that it is possible for their to be downtime or other unexpected technical difficulties.

For a good introduction to the tool and how to use it see the crash course videos posted here.

Signing up

To create an account go to deepnote.com and click the Sign up button on the upper right.

Deepnotes registration process uses either Google or GitHub oauth for identity managment and as such you will need an account with one of these services to register - there is no need to use an existing account for this, you can create a new account with either service that is solely used for this purpose. Both Gooogle and Github should be explicit about any account information that will be shared with Deepnote (e.g.your name and contact information).

After logging in with your service of choice you should be taken to a Getting Started notebook on Deepnote which provides a walk through of some of the basic features of the tool. You can click on your name in the upper left corner to exit the notebook and be taken to your dashboard where you can create new projects.

Billing (its free)

By default, all newly created accounts are placed under Deepnotes free individual plan, this will provide you with 750 hours of compute time per month which should be more than adequate for this and any other course you might be enrolled in.

Getting Workshop materials

Each week we will be providing a link for Deepnote users which will take you to a read-only version of the materials. You will then be able to copy that project into your space on Deepnote by clicking the Duplicate button in the upper right.

Once copied the project can then be opened within your space, and you will be able to edit the workshop notebook (and work through the provided exercises).

Downloading

After completing each worksheet you need to render your notebook to PDF. This PDF will then be turned into via Gradescope, before the deadline, in order to receive credit for that assignment. The rendering process will be detailed in the worksheets, but the resulting PDF (or any other file) can be downloaded by clicking on the ... to the right of a filename and then selecting Download.

Colaboration

If you intend to use Deepnote with teammates (which is recommended) then you will need to share access to a project between all teammates. Note that for the course there is a maximum of 4 members per team (there is also a maximum of three additional collaborators for a private project with Deepnotes individual plan).

We recommend viewing the Real-time collaboration video here for a very brief introduction to these tools.

A standard workflow for each workshop should look as follows :

  • Team member 1 duplicates the project into their space

  • Team member 1 then adds Team members 2-4 to the project with edit permissions.

    • The easiest approach is via the sharing link provided by the menu,

    • Alternatively adding members via email is also possible, keep in mind these will be based on the email addresses used to register your account(s).

  • All team members should now have access to the project and can freely edit any of the files.

  • When completed, one team member submits the PDF to Gradescope and designates all team members (so everyone gets credit)
